Inexorable Decline Coffee Talk
------------------------------

Dylan Byers: The decline of the industry is
no secret to anyone. And obviously, since you=E2=80=99ve left, NBC has spun=
 off MSNBC. Your jurisdiction was always NBC News, but I wonder what you th=
ought when you heard the news that they were going to spin this off, and Ma=
rk Lazarus was going to run the cable companies.

=C2=A0

Noah Oppenheim: I=E2=80=99ve been in these chairs, and I know how difficult=
 all of these decisions are=E2=80=94the big ones and the small
ones=E2=80=94and you=E2=80=99re making dozens of them a day. And from the o=
utside, sometimes the forces influencing those decisions are opaque, and it=
 looks like it=E2=80=99s a bunch of knuckleheads running the show.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

First of all, I think Mark Lazarus is as smart an executive as you=E2=80=99=
ll find. He=E2=80=99s a guy who didn=E2=80=99t shy away from making hard de=
cisions and really tried to figure out how to make this a better business. =
So for
the people at SpinCo, they at least have the benefit of being led by somebo=
dy who I think is courageous in his decision-making, smart, and clear-eyed =
about the business. I think there=E2=80=99s a real opportunity for them to =
do something interesting with it. SpinCo sort of felt like an inevitability=
=2E

=C2=A0

If you want to be optimistic about it, you say this is an opportunity for t=
hem to lean into the strengths of those
brands, unencumbered by consideration for what it might do, for instance, t=
o NBC News. There was always that healthy tension with MSNBC=E2=80=99s grea=
test value, which in my opinion was as a progressive opinion brand. And the=
re was always this pretense to not lean too far in that direction, because =
it might reflect back on the core NBC News brand in ways that weren=E2=80=
=99t helpful. Now they=E2=80=99re liberated. They can say, Alright, we own =
a progressive opinion brand, and let=E2=80=99s see what we can do with
it.

=C2=A0

I understand the future of MSNBC without NBC News, but what=E2=80=99s the f=
uture of NBC News without MSNBC?

=C2=A0

I think parts of it are clearer than others. The easy one is the Today show=
=2E It=E2=80=99s an incredibly healthy l=
ifestyle brand, and I think it=E2=80=
=99s better thought of in that bucket than as a news property.
It is news, and I would still argue that the first 20 minutes of the Today =
show is as good a summary of the day=E2=80=99s news as you can find. And it=
=E2=80=99s obviously anchored by, in my opinion, the best hard news journal=
ist at NBC in Savannah Guthrie. But, its revenue is derived from its lifest=
yle programming and e-commerce business. I think Today probably has a small=
er future than what it was 25 years ago, but I still think it=E2=80=99s a h=
ealthy and profitable one.

=C2=A0

As for the future of an evening newscast at 6:30? You=E2=80=99d think that=
=E2=80=99s the diciest one. Because in a world with ubiquitous news and inf=
ormation at our fingertips on our phones, who needs to sit down every night=
 and have somebody read it to us? With that being said, the audience for th=
ose shows is still sizable. It=E2=80=99s still multiples of the number of p=
eople watching cable news on any given day. So
there=E2=80=99s still something there.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

There seems to be an audience of at least, when you add it up, 20 million p=
eople a day who want to watch a down-the-middle summary of what=E2=80=99s h=
appening in the world. The amount of revenue that throws off is going to co=
ntinue to shrink for a variety of reasons. But there does seem to be an aud=
ience for the product. I think the big question mark=E2=80=94both a challen=
ge and an opportunity=E2=80=94is
whether their streaming product, NBC News Now, can continue to scale. We=E2=
=80=99ve seen the cable universe go in the direction of opinion. That seems=
 to be what people want from them, but maybe there=E2=80=99s still an audie=
nce for a 24/7 hard news product. That=E2=80=99s the niche that NBC News No=
w could potentially fill. I think the jury is still out on that.

Selling Cigarettes
------------------

I see a path for really strong brands like
Today because they have an e-commerce business=E2=80=94and for the people w=
ho are fans of those shows, they feel an immense amount of loyalty toward S=
avannah Guthrie, for instance. You could see something that, on streaming, =
continued to appeal to people as sort of the morning routine. It=E2=80=99s =
harder for me to see that future for the evening news, Meet the Press=E2=80=
=A6

=C2=A0

Yes. Then it becomes not so much Meet the Press or evening news. The questi=
on is: David Muir, or Kristen Welker, or Stephanopoulos? I think there will=
 always be an audience for news presented by trusted figures whom that audi=
ence relates to. I could certainly imagine a world=E2=80=94if David Muir le=
ft ABC tomorrow, and said he was going to launch a product on streaming whe=
re he summarized the day=E2=80=99s
events=E2=80=94I think there are a lot of people in America who love hearin=
g about the world presented by David Muir. I think Kristen Welker, who=E2=
=80=99s doing a terrific job moderating Meet the Press, has an audience as =
much as Meet the Press does as a brand. I think the future for all of this =
is going to be tied probably more to those individual personalities, as you=
=E2=80=99ve seen in the podcast space and the Substack space. Although, I d=
o think those legacy brands retain value,
particularly among older audiences.

=C2=A0

If you=E2=80=99re sitting where Rebecca Kutler is right now, how do you man=
age [the chaos engulfing MSNBC]? Obviously, Rachel Maddow is your biggest s=
tar, but you are also ostensibly the boss of the network, and have a pretty=
 strong conviction in what your game plan is for the next two or three year=
s. What advice can you offer?

=C2=A0

Well, first off, I should say I=E2=80=99m enormously grateful that I=E2=80=
=99m not sitting there. These jobs have always been, and continue to be, qu=
ite difficult. And you=E2=80=99ve identified what has always been an odd dy=
namic in these places, which is that you have the folks who are ostensibly =
in charge, and the on-air stars who make far more money and have far bigger=
 megaphones and a direct line to an audience. So the question of who=E2=80=
=99s
more powerful, or really calling the shots, has always been an interesting =
one in the television business.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I think all one can do in these situations=E2=80=94and it seems like Rebecc=
a and Laz are doing exactly this=E2=80=94is be decisive and be transparent =
with the workforce. It=E2=80=99s hard to work at a legacy media company whe=
n legacy media is going through seismic upheaval. There=E2=80=99s often an =
assumption=E2=80=94this is true of
journalists who cover the business=E2=80=94that those making the decisions =
are intentionally holding back, when in fact it=E2=80=99s often just that i=
t takes time to arrive at a course of action. It takes time to put all the =
pieces in place that are necessary to make it work. You can hold that conve=
rsation and those moves as close to the chest as possible, but the more peo=
ple you bring into those dialogues, the more chances they have to leak.

=C2=A0

And then you make hard decisions, and unfortunately for everyone, change is=
 hard. Sometimes it means forging a new path for oneself, either within the=
 company, or at a different place, or in a different way. But I=E2=80=99d s=
ay again, just act quickly and as decisively as possible. And I haven=E2=80=
=99t seen any reason to think that=E2=80=99s not exactly what they=E2=80=99=
re doing.

=C2=A0

I look at this media landscape and
I think, at the risk of hyperbole, that it is the greatest threat to our na=
tional security. And I say that for the following reason: Every other threa=
t you think about=E2=80=94whether it=E2=80=99s another terror attack, God f=
orbid, or Russia, or a nuclear incident, or climate change=E2=80=94we canno=
t begin to confront any one of these challenges for as long as we exist in =
this paralysis of separate truths.

=C2=A0

And we=E2=80=99ve seen what disunity can do to
countries and how it can very much impact their level of security. I look a=
t it every day, and it=E2=80=99s terrifying to me, as this system has kind =
of hardened into these fiefdoms. In the same way that you could have made a=
 lot of money a long time ago selling cigarettes that really weren=E2=80=99=
t great for people, there are a lot of people now who are selling the civic=
 equivalent of cigarettes. Because the audience wants it; it makes them fee=
l good; they can make a lot of money. But what are we doing to the
country?

Got Any Ideas?
--------------

I think one of two things need to happen here to address the threat:
Either legacy institutions like NBC News need to come up with a really robu=
st strategy for a post-linear future, or one of these new influencers is go=
ing to have to take on Walter Cronkite=E2=80=93level trustworthiness with t=
he American people. I think that=E2=80=99s very uncertain territory ahead.

=C2=A0

For sure. Not only do you need individuals who can amass that kind of
trust and credibility, but what=E2=80=99s lost is that there=E2=80=99s an i=
nfrastructure that=E2=80=99s necessary in order to do this well, if you=E2=
=80=99re trying to capture the most accurate available picture of the truth=
 at any given time. And let=E2=80=99s be clear, journalism is an imperfect =
practice. Part of the crisis in trust is that for a long time, some of thes=
e institutions were not forthcoming enough about how imperfect this all was=
=2E You have a lot of people working ve=
ry hard to get it right, but that does=
 not
mean that they always get it right. But the infrastructure that a large org=
anization like NBC News or CNN has=E2=80=94the standards and practices depa=
rtment, the career ladder, the ability to start as a P.A. and then graduall=
y climb the chain, so that by the time you=E2=80=99re making decisions, you=
=E2=80=99ve got five, six, 10 years of experience under your belt=E2=80=94t=
hose things are critical.

=C2=A0

You can=E2=80=99t just walk out into the world
with a phone and an Instagram account and expect to do responsible journali=
sm consistently over time. You can get it right occasionally, but these sys=
tems weren=E2=80=99t built just for the sake of wasting big corporations=E2=
=80=99 money. They were built because they were deemed to be necessary for =
good reason to make sure that mistakes weren=E2=80=99t made very often. One=
 of the sad pieces of the decline of these legacy institutions is they=E2=
=80=99re replaced by folks who may not have the same philosophical
commitment to pursuing the truth, but also not the resources to do it in a =
way that doesn=E2=80=99t result in a lot of mistakes and inaccuracies.

=C2=A0

So you don=E2=80=99t subscribe to the Elon Musk thesis, =E2=80=9CYou are th=
e media.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

To use another metaphor=E2=80=94like the drug problem, it=E2=80=99s a suppl=
y-and-demand problem. There is a
supply problem in that we have a lot of bad actors out there who are floodi=
ng the zone with intentional falsehoods in pursuit of a malicious agenda. W=
e also have people with ideological agendas who may not be as overtly disho=
nest, but pick and choose their facts to construct a picture that=E2=80=99s=
 useful to their ideological agenda. You=E2=80=99ve got a lot of people con=
tributing to this problem on the supply side.

On the demand side, the audience is choosing to consume this. And
at a certain point, so long as individual consumers click on this stuff and=
 watch this stuff instead of the more staid middle-of-the-road brands, it=
=E2=80=99s on us, because we do have a choice. We can subscribe to responsi=
ble news outlets; we can choose to get our news from reputable sources. But=
 a lot of people at scale would rather scroll through TikTok and do it that=
 way. And I don=E2=80=99t know how you address that issue.

