<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;"><strong><em>Dylan Byers</em></strong><strong>: The decline o=
f the industry is
no secret to anyone. And obviously, since you=E2=80=99ve left, NBC has spun=
 off MSNBC. Your jurisdiction was always NBC News, but I wonder what you th=
ought when you heard the news that they were going to spin this off, and Ma=
rk Lazarus was going to run the cable companies.</strong></p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;"><em>Noah Oppenheim</em>: I=E2=80=99ve been in these chairs, and I know h=
ow difficult all of these decisions are=E2=80=94the big ones and the small
ones=E2=80=94and you=E2=80=99re making dozens of them a day. And from the o=
utside, sometimes the forces influencing those decisions are opaque, and it=
 looks like it=E2=80=99s a bunch of knuckleheads running the show.=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">First of all, I think Mark Lazarus is as smart an executi=
ve as you=E2=80=99ll find. He=E2=80=99s a guy who didn=E2=80=99t shy away f=
rom making hard decisions and really tried to figure out how to make this a=
 better business. So for
the people at SpinCo, they at least have the benefit of being led by somebo=
dy who I think is courageous in his decision-making, smart, and clear-eyed =
about the business. I think there=E2=80=99s a real opportunity for them to =
do something interesting with it. SpinCo sort of felt like an inevitability=
=2E</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">If you want to be optimistic about it, you say this i=
s an opportunity for them to lean into the strengths of those
brands, unencumbered by consideration for what it might do, for instance, t=
o NBC News. There was always that healthy tension with MSNBC=E2=80=99s grea=
test value, which in my opinion was as a progressive opinion brand. And the=
re was always this pretense to not lean too far in that direction, because =
it might reflect back on the core NBC News brand in ways that weren=E2=80=
=99t helpful. Now they=E2=80=99re liberated. They can say, <em>Alright, we =
own a progressive opinion brand, and let=E2=80=99s see what we can do with
it</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;"><strong>I understand the future of MSNBC without NBC News,=
 but what=E2=80=99s the future of NBC News without MSNBC?</strong></p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">I think parts of it are clearer than others. The easy one is th=
e <em>Today </em>show. It=E2=80=99s an incredibly healthy lifestyle brand, =
and I think it=E2=80=99s better thought of in that bucket than as a news pr=
operty.
It <em>is</em> news, and I would still argue that the first 20 minutes of t=
he <em>Today </em>show is as good a summary of the day=E2=80=99s news as yo=
u can find. And it=E2=80=99s obviously anchored by, in my opinion, the best=
 hard news journalist at NBC in <strong>Savannah Guthrie</strong>. But, its=
 revenue is derived from its lifestyle programming and e-commerce business.=
 I think <em>Today</em> probably has a smaller future than what it was 25 y=
ears ago, but I still think it=E2=80=99s a healthy and profitable one.</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">As for the future of an evening newscast at 6:30? You=E2=
=80=99d think that=E2=80=99s the diciest one. Because in a world with ubiqu=
itous news and information at our fingertips on our phones, who needs to si=
t down every night and have somebody read it to us? With that being said, t=
he audience for those shows is still sizable. It=E2=80=99s still <em>multip=
les</em> of the number of people watching cable news on any given day. So
there=E2=80=99s still something there.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">There seems to be an audienc=
e of at least, when you add it up, 20 million people a day who want to watc=
h a down-the-middle summary of what=E2=80=99s happening in the world. The a=
mount of revenue that throws off is going to continue to shrink for a varie=
ty of reasons. But there does seem to be an audience for the product. I thi=
nk the big question mark=E2=80=94both a challenge and an opportunity=E2=80=
=94is
whether their streaming product, NBC News Now, can continue to scale. We=E2=
=80=99ve seen the cable universe go in the direction of opinion. That seems=
 to be what people want from them, but maybe there=E2=80=99s still an audie=
nce for a 24/7 hard news product. That=E2=80=99s the niche that NBC News No=
w could potentially fill. I think the jury is still out on that.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
