28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Selling Cigarettes</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;"><strong>I see a path for really strong brands like
</strong><strong><em>Today</em></strong><strong> because they have an e-com=
merce business=E2=80=94and for the people who are fans of those shows, they=
 feel an immense amount of loyalty toward Savannah Guthrie, for instance. Y=
ou could see something that, on streaming, continued to appeal to people as=
 sort of the morning routine. It=E2=80=99s harder for me to see that future=
 for the evening news, </strong><strong><em>Meet the Press</em></strong><st=
rong>=E2=80=A6</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Yes. Then it becomes not so much <=
em>Meet the Press</em> or evening news. The question is: <strong>David Muir=
</strong>, or <strong>Kristen Welker</strong>, or <strong>Stephanopoulos</s=
trong>? I think there will always be an audience for news presented by trus=
ted figures whom that audience relates to. I could certainly imagine a worl=
d=E2=80=94if David Muir left ABC tomorrow, and said he was going to launch =
a product on streaming where he summarized the day=E2=80=99s
events=E2=80=94I think there are a lot of people in America who love hearin=
g about the world presented by David Muir. I think Kristen Welker, who=E2=
=80=99s doing a terrific job moderating <em>Meet the Press</em>, has an aud=
ience as much as <em>Meet the Press</em> does as a brand. I think the futur=
e for <em>all </em>of this is going to be tied probably more to those indiv=
idual personalities, as you=E2=80=99ve seen in the podcast space and the Su=
bstack space. Although, I do think those legacy brands retain value,
particularly among older audiences.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>If you=E2=
=80=99re sitting where Rebecca Kutler is right now, how do you manage [the =
chaos engulfing MSNBC]? Obviously, Rachel Maddow is your biggest star, but =
you are also ostensibly the boss of the network, and have a pretty strong c=
onviction in what your game plan is for the next two or three years. What a=
dvice can you offer?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Well=
, first off, I should say I=E2=80=99m enormously grateful that I=E2=80=99m =
<em>not </em>sitting there. These jobs have always been, and continue to be=
, quite difficult. And you=E2=80=99ve identified what has always been an od=
d dynamic in these places, which is that you have the folks who are ostensi=
bly in charge, and the on-air stars who make far more money and have far bi=
gger megaphones and a direct line to an audience. So the question of who=E2=
=80=99s
more powerful, or really calling the shots, has always been an interesting =
one in the television business.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I think all one c=
an do in these situations=E2=80=94and it seems like Rebecca and Laz are doi=
ng exactly this=E2=80=94is be decisive and be transparent with the workforc=
e. It=E2=80=99s hard to work at a legacy media company when legacy media is=
 going through seismic upheaval. There=E2=80=99s often an assumption=E2=80=
=94this is true of
journalists who cover the business=E2=80=94that those making the decisions =
are intentionally holding back, when in fact it=E2=80=99s often just that i=
t takes time to arrive at a course of action. It takes time to put all the =
pieces in place that are necessary to make it work. You can hold that conve=
rsation and those moves as close to the chest as possible, but the more peo=
ple you bring into those dialogues, the more chances they have to leak.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:
0;margin-bottom:0px;">And then you make hard decisions, and unfortunately f=
or everyone, change is hard. Sometimes it means forging a new path for ones=
elf, either within the company, or at a different place, or in a different =
way. But I=E2=80=99d say again, just act quickly and as decisively as possi=
ble. And I haven=E2=80=99t seen any reason to think that=E2=80=99s not exac=
tly what they=E2=80=99re doing.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I look at this media la=
ndscape and
I think, at the risk of hyperbole, that it is the greatest threat to our na=
tional security. And I say that for the following reason: Every other threa=
t you think about=E2=80=94whether it=E2=80=99s another terror attack, God f=
orbid, or Russia, or a nuclear incident, or climate change=E2=80=94we canno=
t begin to confront any one of these challenges for as long as we exist in =
this paralysis of separate truths.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">And we=E2=80=99ve seen what disunity c=
an do to
countries and how it can very much impact their level of security. I look a=
t it every day, and it=E2=80=99s terrifying to me, as this system has kind =
of hardened into these fiefdoms. In the same way that you could have made a=
 lot of money a long time ago selling cigarettes that really weren=E2=80=99=
t great for people, there are a lot of people now who are selling the civic=
 equivalent of cigarettes. Because the audience wants it; it makes them fee=
l good; they can make a lot of money. But what are we doing to the
country?</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
